land or Nottinghamshire, or Blythe in Warwickshire, named for the rivers on which they stand. The river name is from Old English <i>blīthe</i> ‘gentle, pleasant’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bligh","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Blythe  , with Anglo-Norman loss of <i>th</i>.","Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of <b>Ó Blighe</b> ‘descendant of <i>Blighe</i>’, probably a Gaelicized form of the Old Norse byname <i>Blígr</i> (from <i>blígja</i> ‘to gaze’).","Cornish: nickname from Cornish <i>blyth</i> ‘wolf’. Compare   Blethen  ."]},{"name":"Blyth","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Blythe  ."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Meldrum","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from a place in Aberdeenshire, firstrecorded in 1291 as <i>Melgedrom</i>, from an obscure first element +Gaelic <i>druim</i> ‘ridge’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander Meldrum Blythe, I was born in 1415, in Kennoway, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Blythe, was 35 and his mother, Sarah McCall, was 30. He died in 1458, in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1415–1458":"1415–1458","1410–1480":"1